The screen has been entirely black for ~30 seconds. This is suspicious. Let me investigate more - check the QEMU process status, try sending keystrokes, and look at the boot configuration more carefully.

{
  "analysis": "The VM screen remains entirely black after 25+ seconds. This could indicate: 1) The boot process is stuck, 2) The display output isn't being captured correctly, 3) The image might need DOS as a base OS since Windows 3.11 runs on top of DOS. Let me investigate the QEMU process and try interacting with it.",
  "plan": "1. Check QEMU process CPU usage. 2. Try sending keyboard input to see if the screen changes. 3. Check QEMU configuration more carefully. 4. Consider that Windows 3.11 for Workgroups needs DOS underneath - maybe the image has a DOS boot with Windows auto-starting.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ps aux | grep qemu\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'info cpus' | socat - UNIX-CONNECT:/tmp/qemu-monitor.sock\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'info block' | socat - UNIX-CONNECT:/tmp/qemu-monitor.sock\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo 'sendkey ret' | socat - UNIX-CONNECT:/tmp/qemu-monitor.sock\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "sleep 3 && echo 'screendump /tmp/vm-screen6.ppm' | socat - UNIX-CONNECT:/tmp/qemu-monitor.sock\n",
      "duration": 5.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "python3 -c \"\nwith open('/tmp/vm-screen6.ppm', 'rb') as f:\n    data = f.read()\nprint(f'Size: {len(data)}')\nprint(f'Dimensions: {data[:20]}')\npixels = data.split(b'\\n', 2)[2]\nnz = sum(1 for i in range(0,len(pixels),3) if pixels[i:i+3] != b'\\x00\\x00\\x00')\nprint(f'Non-black pixels: {nz}')\n\"\n",
      "duration": 2.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

